Credit: Marvel Studios

Ever since Captain Marvel soared into theatres, fans have had one unending question.

“Where has Carol been?”

It’s a fair question. Earth has, well, she’s been through a lot since the 90s. Nick Fury (Samuel L Jackson) may have been pressing that button, but Carol (Brie Larson) has not been answering.

In the first clip for Avengers: Endgame, she gives an extremely valid…

summary: Wow, Brie Larson really made me feel THAT related to Kit in "Unicorn store". I felt that movie so much, the feeling of "growing...
body: Wow, Brie Larson really made me feel THAT related to Kit in “Unicorn store”. I felt that movie so much, the feeling of “growing up” but still want to do or dream about things that adults “should not” want to do or dream about, the feeling of being lonely, unwanted and being a complete failure all the time. I didn’t expect that from the movie, but it really touched me, especially that scene when Kit tells the unicorn to love the other woman even when she thinks that no one loves her, damn, i cried my heart out then. Tysm, Brie.

summary: //I can honestly say The Unicorn Store is a great movie, particularly for any eighties kid who ever felt embarrassed for being...
body: //I can honestly say The Unicorn Store is a great movie, particularly for any eighties kid who ever felt embarrassed for being weird and creative.  No “bullshit social justice gold stars” (a conspiracy theory of reactionaries anyway) about it, it is objectively a good indie film. Be prepared for a lot of quirkiness, but it’s done effectively, and not just to be self-consciously “weird.”
